	abstract = {{\textless}p{\textgreater}{\textless}strong class="journal-contentHeaderColor"{\textgreater}Abstract.{\textless}/strong{\textgreater} We compare the performance of five different regional climate models (RCMs) (COSMO-CLM{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}, HIRHAM5, MAR3.10, MetUM, and RACMO2.3p2), forced by ERA-Interim reanalysis, in simulating the near-surface climate and surface mass balance (SMB) of Antarctica. All models simulate Antarctic climate well when compared with daily observed temperature and pressure, with nudged models matching daily observations slightly better than free-running models. The ensemble mean annual SMB over the Antarctic ice sheet (AIS) including ice shelves is {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}2329¬±94{\textless}/span{\textgreater} Gt yr{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{‚àí1}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} over the common 1987‚Äì2015 period covered by all models. There is large interannual variability, consistent between models due to variability in the driving ERA-Interim reanalysis. Mean annual SMB is sensitive to the chosen period; over our 30-year climatological mean period (1980 to 2010), the ensemble mean is 2483 Gt yr{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{‚àí1}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}. However, individual model estimates vary from {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}1961¬±70{\textless}/span{\textgreater} to {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}2519¬±118{\textless}/span{\textgreater} Gt yr{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{‚àí1}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}. The largest spatial differences between model SMB estimates are in West Antarctica, the Antarctic Peninsula, and around the Transantarctic Mountains. We find no significant trend in Antarctic SMB over either period. Antarctic ice sheet (AIS) mass loss is currently