	abstract = {An X-band polarimetric radar was deployed in the eastern Swiss Alps at an altitude of 2133 m. Radar measurements were complemented with several weather stations deployed in an altitude range from 1500 to 3100 m as well as with a Ô¨Åxed GPS ground station that was used to infer integrated water vapor estimates. Around 8000 vertical proÔ¨Åles of polarimetric radar observables above the melting layer collected during two months are analyzed. First, the behavior of the mean proÔ¨Åles of reÔ¨Çectivity at horizontal polarization Zh, differential reÔ¨Çectivity Zdr, copolar cross correlation rhv, and speciÔ¨Åc differential phase shift Kdp are interpreted from a microphysical point of view. It is shown that the whole evolution of snowÔ¨Çakes, from pristine crystals at temperatures around 2308C to dendritic crystals around 2158C, to large aggregates around 08C, is well captured by the polarimetric radar variables. In a second step, the proÔ¨Åles are analyzed as functions of high and low water vapor and snow accumulation conditions. It is found that the vertical proÔ¨Åles of polarimetric radar variables have distinct features in low versus high water vapor conditions. High water vapor conditions appear to favor the occurrence of crystal aggregates at high altitudes/low temperatures. It is shown with a hydrometeor identiÔ¨Åcation scheme that graupel-like particles are found to be dominant right above the melting layer for snow events with high accumulation intensities. The present analyses show that measurements from X-band dual-polarization radar can be useful to characterize the dominant microphysical processes during precipitation in mountainous regions.},
