	abstract = {We present improvements over our previous approach to automatic winter hydrometeor classiÔ¨Åcation by means of convolutional neural networks (CNNs), using more data and improved training techniques to achieve higher accuracy on a more complicated dataset than we had previously demonstrated. As an advancement of our previous proof of concept study, this work demonstrates broader usefulness of deep CNNs by using a substantially larger and more diverse dataset, which we make publicly available, from many more snow events. We describe the collection, processing, and sorting of this dataset of over 25 000 high-quality Multi-Angle SnowÔ¨Çake Camera (MASC) image chips split nearly evenly between Ô¨Åve geometric classes: aggregate, columnar crystal, planar crystal, graupel, and small particle. Raw images were collected over 32 snowfall events between November 2014 and May 2016 near Greeley, Colorado, and were processed with an automated cropping and normalization algorithm to yield 224 3 224 pixel images containing possible hydrometeors. From the bulk set of over 8 400 000 extracted images, a smaller dataset of 14 793 images was sorted by image quality and recognizability (Q\&R) using manual inspection. A presorting network trained on the Q\&R dataset was applied to all 8 400 0001 images to automatically collect a subset of 283 351 good snowÔ¨Çake images. Roughly 5000 representative examples were then collected from this subset manually for each of the Ô¨Åve geometric classes. With a higher emphasis on inclass variety than our previous work, the Ô¨Ånal dataset yields trained networks that better capture the imperfect cases and diverse forms that occur within the broad categories studied to achieve an accuracy of 96.2\% on a vastly more challenging dataset.},
