	abstract = {Simulated radar signatures within the melting layer in stratiform rain‚Äînamely, the radar bright band‚Äîare checked by means of comparisons with simultaneous measurements of the bright band made by the ER-2 Doppler radar (EDOP; X band) and Cloud Radar System (CRS; W band) airborne Doppler radars during the Cirrus Regional Study of Tropical Anvils and Cirrus Layers‚ÄìFlorida-Area Cirrus Experiment (CRYSTALFACE) campaign in 2002. A stratiÔ¨Åed-sphere model, allowing the fractional water content to vary along the radius of the particle, is used to compute the scattering properties of individual melting snowÔ¨Çakes. Using the effective dielectric constants computed by the conjugate gradient‚Äìfast Fourier transform numerical method for X and W bands and expressing the fractional water content of a melting particle as an exponential function in particle radius, it is found that at X band the simulated radar brightband proÔ¨Åles are in an excellent agreement with the measured proÔ¨Åles. It is also found that the simulated W-band proÔ¨Åles usually resemble the shapes of the measured brightband proÔ¨Åles even though persistent offsets between them are present. These offsets, however, can be explained by the attenuation caused by cloud water and water vapor at W band. This is conÔ¨Årmed by comparisons of the radar proÔ¨Åles made in the rain regions where the unattenuated W-band reÔ¨Çectivity proÔ¨Åles can be estimated through the X- and W-band Doppler velocity measurements. The brightband model described in this paper has the potential to be used effectively for both radar and radiometer algorithms relevant to the satellite-based Tropical Rainfall Measuring Mission and Global Precipitation Measuring Mission.},
